item.title: [HBASE-7372] Check in the generated website so can point apache infrastructure at what to publish as our hbase.apache.org
item.description:
January 1st is deadline for changing how we publish our website. We may no longer rsync out to people.apache.org. Apache infrastructure supplies two options here: http://www.apache.org/dev/project-site.html We could redo our site in apache cms format. Or we could just use svnpubsub and keep on w/ how the site is currently generated and on checkin, have it autopublished. I'll go the latter route unless I hear otherwise.

For svnpubsub, we need to point apache infrastructure at a directory that has our checkedin site in it. I was thinking $

{hbasedir}

/hbase.apache.org

Let me raise this on the dev list too.
item.summary: Check in the generated website so can point apache infrastructure at what to publish as our hbase.apache.org

status.description: A resolution has been taken, and it is awaiting verification by reporter. From here issues are either reopened, or are closed.

comments.comment: What will the workflow look like? Commit docbook changes into the existing svn path, generate the site into the new path, and commit the results? That seems tedious. Then again, maybe this is better than maintaining the raw HTML manually?

Nick Dimiduk It'll be similar to how it currently is. Check in docbook and xdoc changes as you go. Independently, if you thnk it time to publish a new version of website, you'd run 'mvn site site:stage'. site:stage will copy the generated site to ./hbase.apache.org (if we apply the patch I'm attaching). You'd then commit it locally. That'll trigger the deploy on apache servers.

Previous, it was about the same amount of gymnastics....we'd do site:deploy instead of site:stage and it would rsync what was generated by 'mvn site' over to people.apache.org. From there it'd be rsync'd automatically out to apache frontends.

I tried to get site:deploy to deploy locally rather than copy over to people.apache.org only, when I change the target url to be hbase.apache.org, it goes and puts hbase.apache.org in all sub-modules.... ugly. When I was young and headstrong rather than as I am now, old and headstrong, I would try and wrestle maven into doing what I wanted. I don't do that anymore.

When I was young and headstrong rather than as I am now, old and headstrong, I would try and wrestle maven into doing what I wanted. I don't do that anymore

These bits of humor of yours on various JIRAs are great.

I looked at making an hbase-site module. After messing with it for a while – in spite of my axiom above – I think its probably better to leave it as is. The site generation is made up from all hbase-* content so you want some kinda of meta perspective when building it. Trying to move the top-level site src stuff... src/docbkx, etc. – down into hbase-site would take a bunch of messing regen'ing the site and messing in poms. I'll leave it as is. We can try it at another time.

I'll not add a patch here. Its 10MB. I did this to generate the content:

MAVEN_OPTS=" -Xmx3g" mvn -DskipTests site:stage -DstagingDirectory=./hbase.apache.org

I added a README.txt which talked about the content being auto-generated and how to do it and that one day, when you commit to this dir, it'll show up on http://hbase.apache.org.

Let me commit.

Ugh. The checkin is massive. I hate having to check in a generated site. The alternative is switching how we do our website going over to the apache cms system. It'd be an undertaking (I guess). This is the alternative. Hadoop checks in its website (not that that makes it right). On bright side, it might now be easier for others updating the website.
Let me amend. The jxr x-ref stuff, while nice, makes up 60M of this 80M commit (I thought it was 10M). Removing this plugin and its generated content.

Integrated in HBase-TRUNK-on-Hadoop-2.0.0 #302 (See https://builds.apache.org/job/HBase-TRUNK-on-Hadoop-2.0.0/302/)
